    </div>

    <!-- SECTION 2: WHAT THE CLINICAL STUDIES SHOW -->
    <h2>What the Clinical Studies Show</h2>

    <p>The timeline claims in this guide are not based on anecdotal reports or manufacturer marketing. They come from peer-reviewed, randomized, double-blind, placebo-controlled clinical trials — the gold standard of medical evidence. Here are the four most important studies that establish ashwagandha's timeline of action.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="book-open" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Study 1: Chandrasekhar et al. (2012)</h4>
        <p><strong>64 adults with chronic stress. 600mg KSM-66 daily for 60 days.</strong> The ashwagandha group showed a 27.9% reduction in serum cortisol and a 69.7% reduction in perceived stress (PSS scale) compared to 11.6% for placebo. Significant differences emerged at the 30-day mark and continued improving through day 60. Published in <em>Indian Journal of Psychological Medicine</em>.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="book-open" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Study 2: Langade et al. (2019)</h4>
        <p><strong>80 healthy adults. 600mg ashwagandha root extract daily for 8 weeks.</strong> Sleep quality improved significantly by week 6, with improvements in sleep onset latency, total sleep time, and sleep efficiency. Both healthy sleepers and insomnia patients benefited, but insomnia patients showed larger improvements. Published in <em>Cureus</em>.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="book-open" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Study 3: Wankhede et al. (2015)</h4>
        <p><strong>57 young men in a resistance training program. 600mg KSM-66 daily for 8 weeks.</strong> The ashwagandha group had significantly greater increases in muscle strength (bench press +46kg vs +26kg) and muscle size compared to placebo. Testosterone increased by 96.2 ng/dL in the ashwagandha group vs 18 ng/dL in placebo. Published in <em>Journal of the International Society of Sports Nutrition</em>.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="book-open" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Study 4: Lopresti et al. (2019)</h4>
        <p><strong>60 adults with self-reported anxiety. 240mg Shoden ashwagandha daily for 60 days.</strong> Morning cortisol decreased significantly, and DASS-21 anxiety and stress scores improved compared to placebo. Notable: this study used a lower dose of a high-concentration extract (35% withanolides) and still produced results within 60 days. Published in <em>Medicine</em>.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p>The pattern across all studies is consistent: measurable biochemical changes (cortisol, testosterone, DHEA-S) appear at 4-8 weeks, while subjective improvements in mood, stress tolerance, and sleep quality can begin as early as 2-4 weeks. No study showed significant effects before the 2-week mark. If you want a deeper analysis of ashwagandha's anxiety-specific mechanisms and clinical evidence, read our comprehensive guide on <a href="/blog/ashwagandha-for-anxiety/">ashwagandha for anxiety</a>.</p>

    <!-- SECTION 3: ASHWAGANDHA FOR STRESS -->
    <h2>Ashwagandha for Stress: When to Expect Results</h2>

    <p>Stress reduction is ashwagandha's most well-documented benefit and the one with the fastest onset. This is because ashwagandha directly modulates the HPA axis — the neuroendocrine system that controls cortisol production. When you are chronically stressed, the HPA axis becomes dysregulated and cortisol levels remain elevated even when no acute threat is present. Ashwagandha normalizes this axis by reducing the sensitivity of cortisol receptors and downregulating ACTH release from the pituitary gland.</p>

    <div class="key-stat">
      <span class="key-stat-num">2-4 wks</span>
      <p class="key-stat-txt">is the typical timeline for initial stress relief with 600mg KSM-66 ashwagandha daily. By <strong>day 30</strong>, the Chandrasekhar 2012 trial measured statistically significant reductions in both serum cortisol and perceived stress scores compared to placebo. Full effects continued building through day 60.</p>
    </div>

    <h3>What "stress reduction" actually feels like</h3>

    <p>Ashwagandha does not produce a noticeable "calming sensation" like L-theanine or GABA. The effect is more subtle: you realize that situations that previously triggered anxiety or irritability no longer provoke the same intensity of response. You may sleep more easily, recover faster from stressful events, and feel less overwhelmed by your daily responsibilities. Many people describe it as "taking the edge off" without sedation or cognitive impairment.</p>

    <p>The mechanism is cortisol-dependent, which means ashwagandha works best for people whose stress is driven by elevated cortisol. If your cortisol levels are already normal (you are not chronically stressed), you may not notice a dramatic difference. This is one reason why responses vary between individuals. For targeted cortisol support, see our guide to the best <a href="/trending/cortisol-gummies/">cortisol gummies</a>.</p>

    <div class="tip-box">
