      <span class="warn-box-ico">⚠️</span>
      <p><strong>Important:</strong> Ashwagandha is not a replacement for professional mental health treatment. If you have been diagnosed with generalized anxiety disorder, panic disorder, or PTSD, work with your healthcare provider to determine whether ashwagandha is appropriate as a complementary intervention alongside evidence-based therapy and/or medication. Do not discontinue prescribed medications to take ashwagandha.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- SECTION 5: ASHWAGANDHA FOR SLEEP -->
    <h2>Ashwagandha for Sleep: When to Expect Results</h2>

    <p>Ashwagandha is not a sedative — it does not make you drowsy or induce sleep directly. Instead, it improves sleep by addressing the root causes that prevent sleep: elevated cortisol, HPA axis hyperactivation, and anxiety-driven hyperarousal. This indirect mechanism means the sleep benefits unfold gradually as cortisol normalizes and the nervous system shifts from sympathetic (fight-or-flight) to parasympathetic (rest-and-digest) dominance.</p>

    <p>The Langade 2019 study is the most relevant trial for sleep outcomes. It enrolled 80 healthy adults and randomized them to 600mg ashwagandha root extract or placebo for 8 weeks. Key findings:</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="moon" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Sleep Onset Latency</h4>
        <p>Time to fall asleep decreased significantly in the ashwagandha group. Insomnia patients showed the greatest improvement — falling asleep an average of 28 minutes faster by study end.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="star" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Sleep Quality Score</h4>
        <p>Pittsburgh Sleep Quality Index (PSQI) scores improved significantly. The ashwagandha group reported better subjective sleep quality, less daytime dysfunction, and fewer nighttime awakenings.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="clock" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Sleep Efficiency</h4>
        <p>The percentage of time in bed spent actually sleeping increased in both healthy sleepers and insomnia patients, with insomnia patients showing larger gains.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="zap" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Non-Restorative Sleep</h4>
        <p>Feelings of unrefreshing sleep and morning grogginess decreased. Participants reported waking up feeling more rested and alert.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p>For sleep specifically, expect initial improvements in sleep onset (falling asleep faster) within 2-3 weeks, with more substantial improvements in overall sleep quality and efficiency at 6-10 weeks. If your insomnia is primarily driven by anxiety and racing thoughts, the timeline may be closer to the anxiety timeline (6-8 weeks). For a comprehensive overview of all sleep-support supplements in gummy form, visit our <a href="/best-sleep-gummies/">best sleep gummies</a> guide.</p>

